    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nNumPy has a check in `np.ndarray.resize` behind the `refcheck` keyword argument:\n\nhttps://numpy.org/devdocs/reference/generated/numpy.ndarray.resize.html\n\nOn Python 3.13 and older, the check allows objects to be resized if their reference count is less than or equal to 2.\n\nOn Python 3.14, we can no longer use the same check, because Python now elides increfs and decrefs for function locals. That means the original check, which allows arrays with reference counts of two to be resized, will now allow function local variables that are aliased to be resized. We definitely don't want that, so I made the check use `PyUnstable_Object_IsUniquelyReferenced` in https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30278.\n\nHowever, it turns out (https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/30991), this doesn't fix the issue in Cython functions or in module-scope variables.\n\nI'm curious if the Cython maintainers consider the different reference count behavior for Cython and Python functions to be a Cython bug.\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\nSee https://github.com/ngoldbaum/test-cython\n\nIf I build and run the code in the linked repository with the latest stable releases of NumPy and Cython on Python 3.14, I see:\n\n```\ngoldbaum at Nathans-MBP in ~/Documents/test\n○  python -c \"import test_resize\"\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<string>\", line 1, in <module>\n    import test_resize\n  File \"/Users/goldbaum/.pyenv/versions/3.14.3-debug/lib/python3.14/site-packages/test_resize/__init__.py\", line 5, in <module>\n    test()\n    ~~~~^^\n  File \"test_cython/test.pyx\", line 5, in test_cython.test.test\n    a.resize((2, 1))\nValueError: cannot resize an array that references or is referenced\nby another array in this way.\nUse the np.resize function or refcheck=False\n\ngoldbaum at Nathans-MBP in ~/Documents/test\n○  python -VV\nPython 3.14.3 (main, Mar 11 2026, 15:42:04) [Clang 17.0.0 (clang-1700.6.4.2)]\n```\n\nHowever, on Python 3.13, everything works fine:\n\n```\ngoldbaum at Nathans-MBP in ~/Documents/test\n○  python -c \"import test_resize\"\n\ngoldbaum at Nathans-MBP in ~/Documents/test\n○  python -VV\nPython 3.13.9 (main, Dec  5 2025, 09:11:02) [Clang 17.0.0 (clang-1700.4.4.1)]\n```\n\nThe relevant code in NumPy is here:\n\nhttps://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/b981a5fc0f046491cec54557a6bb4438eef98453/numpy/_core/src/multiarray/shape.c#L88-L102\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nBoth `test` and `test_py` run without error.\n\n### OS\n\nMacOS\n\n### Python version\n\n3.14.3\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.2.4\n\n### Additional context\n\nThis originally came up in a NumPy issue: https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/30991",
