            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I have a distant memory that we've had issues in the past with refcounting and Numpy's temporary elision. I've failed to find an issue with a quick search though.  That's obviously less serious because it's a missed optimization rather than something not working.\n\n> I'm curious if the Cython maintainers consider the different reference count behavior for Cython and Python functions to be a Cython bug.\n\nMy view would be \"no\". A few reasons:\n* In a similar toy example I can get different refcounting depending on if we are using `Py_LIMITED_API=0x030A0000` (i.e. pre-vectorcall) or not. I don't think that's necessarily fixable.\n* Even in post-vectorcall Stable ABI, we'd need to make runtime decisions on whether to reference-count to try to keep it consistent.\n* I don't actually thing we can do as well as Python here. For example, if you run this code in Python 3.14 you get \"1\":\n    ```\n    import sys\n\n    class C:\n        def f(self, a, b):\n            print(sys.getrefcount(self))\n\n    def py_test():\n        c = C()\n        c.f(1,2)\n    \n    py_test()\n    ```\n\n    calling `py_test` from Cython (but not compiling the rest of it) currently gives you 3. I think it could be reduced to 2 at best.  I believe that the Python interpreter has sufficient visibility into its own working when going through a pure-Python call stack that it could eliminate more than us.\n\n-----\n\nHowever, there does look to be an unnecessary reference-count on the `self` argument of Cython calls that I think we could eliminate in most cases (i.e. if we know that the variable is local and not in a closure then it can't be re-assigned to is safe to not reference-count).",
